data.content:
Use MSTest's built-in collection and value assertions for better failure messages:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));  // no built-in "all match" assertion
    var admin = users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin);
}
```

Key replacements:

| Instead of | Use |
|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count)` (or `CollectionAssert.That.HasCount(3)` in MSTest 3.8+) |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(obj != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(obj)` |

Also useful for collections:
- **`CollectionAssert.Contains(collection, item)`** — checks membership
- **`CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(collection)`**
- **`CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual)`** — same items, any order
- **`CollectionAssert.IsSubsetOf(subset, superset)`**

`Assert.AreEqual(expected, actual)` gives you the actual vs expected values on failure, while `Assert.IsTrue` only says "expected true, got false."
